{{citation style|date=December 2014}}
{{orphan|date=December 2014}}
The {{Nihongo|'''Religious Organizations Law'''|宗教団体法|Shūkyō Dantai Hō}} was passed by the [[Japanese Diet]] in 1939 and enacted in 1940.<ref>Imperial-Way Zen: Ichikawa Hakugen's Critique and Lingering Questions for ...By Christopher Ives Page 39</ref> The law gave the state authority control over religious organizations.<ref>Japanese Rinzai Zen Buddhism By Jørn Borup Page 29</ref> Following Japan's defeat in [[World War II]], the Religious Organizations Law was [[abrogated]] on December 28 1945, being replaced by the "Religious Corporations Ordinance".<ref>Religion in Japanese History  By Joseph Mitsuo Kitagawa Page 271</ref>

==See also==
[[Peace Preservation Law]]

